1. Understanding the Basics
a. Networking Fundamentals
•	Learn about IP addressing, DNS, HTTP/HTTPS, TCP/IP, and load balancing.
•	Understand VPNs, firewalls, and how networks interact with cloud services.
b. Operating Systems
•	Proficiency in Linux/Unix (commands, shell scripting, system monitoring).
•	Familiarity with Windows Server environments.
c. Programming Skills
•	Learn a scripting language (e.g., Python, Bash, PowerShell).
•	Understand JSON and YAML for configurations.
d. Virtualization Concepts
•	Familiarity with virtualization technologies like VMware, Hyper-V, or VirtualBox.
________________________________________
2. Core Cloud Concepts
a. Cloud Fundamentals
•	Understand the concepts of IaaS, PaaS, SaaS.
•	Learn about cloud service models and deployment models (public, private, hybrid).
b. Major Cloud Providers
Focus on one or more:
•	AWS (Amazon Web Services): S3, EC2, IAM, Lambda, VPC, RDS.
•	Microsoft Azure: Virtual Machines, Blob Storage, Azure AD, Functions, Networking.
•	Google Cloud Platform (GCP): Compute Engine, Cloud Storage, Kubernetes Engine.
________________________________________
3. Hands-On Practice
a. Set Up a Cloud Environment
•	Create free-tier accounts on AWS, Azure, or GCP.
•	Deploy and configure virtual machines, storage solutions, and networking.
b. Basic Cloud Tools
•	Learn the basics of CLI and SDK for the cloud provider of your choice.
•	Explore infrastructure-as-code tools like Terraform or CloudFormation.
________________________________________
4. Advanced Cloud Skills
a. Infrastructure as Code (IaC)
•	Tools: Terraform, AWS CloudFormation, or Azure Resource Manager (ARM).
•	Master configuration management tools: Ansible, Chef, or Puppet.
b. Containers and Orchestration
•	Learn Docker for containerization.
•	Study Kubernetes for orchestration (e.g., GKE, EKS, or AKS).
c. DevOps Practices
•	Learn CI/CD concepts and tools: Jenkins, GitLab CI/CD, AWS CodePipeline.
•	Automate workflows using scripts and cloud services.
d. Cloud Security
•	Master Identity and Access Management (IAM).
•	Learn about encryption, key management, and security tools specific to your cloud provider.
e. Monitoring and Logging
•	Tools: CloudWatch (AWS), Azure Monitor, Prometheus, Grafana.
________________________________________
5. Certifications (Optional but Highly Recommended)
Certifications validate your skills and boost your employability. Consider these:
Beginner Level:
•	AWS Certified Cloud Practitioner
•	Microsoft Azure Fundamentals (AZ-900)
•	Google Cloud Digital Leader
Intermediate Level:
•	AWS Certified Solutions Architect – Associate
•	Microsoft Azure Administrator (AZ-104)
•	Google Associate Cloud Engineer
Advanced Level:
•	AWS Certified DevOps Engineer – Professional
•	Microsoft Azure Solutions Architect Expert
•	Google Professional Cloud Architectgiy